Data transformation and manipulation

Author

Saar Alon-Barkat

Published

May 1, 2024

Importing Libraries

Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)

In this session, we will practice data transformation and data manipulation techniques which are extremely important for working with data. In fact, in most data projects, most of your time will be spent on this.

We will divide the techniques to 4 different categories:

  1. Organizing the dataset

  2. Transforming variables

  3. Aggregating the data

  4. Combining/merging different datasets

We will also learn how to âreshapeâ the data (from long to wide and vice versa).

We will work mainly with the localities dataset, already available in the shared dropbox. This dataset is based on the local authorities dataset published by the CBS.

Before starting - a general comment is needed about working with datasets as objects in R. In R, every table is an object (called âdataframeâ), which can be saved in the working environment. When you make transformations to your data, you can do one of three things:

  1. Printing the results without saving it. This is handy if you donât think you will conduct additional analyses on the table, and you just want to view it. (Usually this is what we will do with arrange and select).

  2. Saving the results as a new object, assigned with a new name. This is handy if you will want to continue using the previous table without the changes.(Usually this is what we will do with filter, and left_join).

  3. Overriding the existing table. Saving the results as the existing table, using the same name. This is handy if you do not think you will use the previous table. (Usually this is what we will do with mutate).

2. Transforming variables (with mutate)

With mutate we can create new variables or override existing variables.

The code will be usually: data %>% mutate(new_var = ...)

For example - letâs create a year variable that will receive 2022 for all raws. Letâs save it into the dataset (override).

Code 
localities_2022 <- localities_2022 %>% 
mutate(year = 2022)

Transforming variables based on logical rules with case_when

case_when allows us to transform not only categorical variables but also numeric variables.

Code 
localities_2022 <- localities_2022 %>% 
  mutate(arab_locality_1 = case_when(
    percent_arab==100 ~ "Arab",
    percent_arab==0 ~ "Jewish",
    TRUE ~ "Mixed"
  )
  )

3. Aggregating the data (with group_by and summarize)

Often we want to aggregate/group/cluster to a higher level.

For this, we can use group_by and summarise. The code will be usually: data %>% group_by(group_var) %>% summarize(...)

For example, letâs aggregate the data at the district level.

Code 
localities_2022 %>%
